motes glucose uptake and glycogen synthesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary metabolic effects of insulin include \u003Cstrong\u003Epromoting glucose uptake and glycogen synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E. Insulin stimulates translocation of GLUT4 glucose transporters to the cell membrane in muscle and adipose tissue, facilitating glucose entry. It also activates glycogen synthase while inhibiting glycogen phosphorylase, leading to net glycogen storage.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - Insulin actually inhibits these processes; glucagon promotes them\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases lipolysis and fatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E - Insulin inhibits lipolysis and promotes lipogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes protein breakdown and amino acid release\u003C/strong\u003E - Insulin has an anabolic effect on protein metabolism, promoting synthesis and inhibiting breakdown\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances ketone body production and secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Insulin suppresses ketogenesis by inhibiting fatty acid breakdown\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOverall, insulin promotes energy storage through multiple pathways while inhibiting catabolic processes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin promotes glucose uptake into cells via GLUT4 transporters in muscle and adipose tissue.","Insulin stimulates glycogen synthesis and inhibits glycogen breakdown.","Insulin promotes lipogenesis and inhibits lipolysis in adipose tissue."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and 